You are debugging a production issue where a high-throughput microservice is experiencing out-of-memory (`java.lang.OutOfMemoryError`) errors. A senior engineer implemented a custom tracking cache using a `WeakHashMap` to associate active worker `Thread` objects with their diagnostic metadata. Here is the implementation:

java
@Service
public class ThreadDiagnosticService {
    private final Map<Thread, DiagnosticInfo> diagnosticCache = new WeakHashMap<>();

    @Transactional
    public synchronized void registerThread(Thread thread, String phase) {
        diagnosticCache.put(thread, new DiagnosticInfo(thread, phase));
    }

    public static class DiagnosticInfo {
        private final Thread threadRef;
        private final String phase;

        public DiagnosticInfo(Thread threadRef, String phase) {
            this.threadRef = threadRef;
            this.phase = phase;
        }
    }
}

You are debugging a production issue where a multi-tenant Spring Boot application leaks tenant context (data from Tenant A is visible to Tenant B) under heavy load. The tenant context is managed using a custom thread-local collection context:

java
public class TenantContextHolder {
    private static final ThreadLocal<TenantContext> contextHolder = new ThreadLocal<>();

    public static void setContext(TenantContext context) {
        contextHolder.set(context);
    }

    public static TenantContext getContext() {
        return contextHolder.get();
    }

    public static void clear() {
        contextHolder.remove();
    }
}


The context is set inside a custom Spring Web Interceptor. However, during asynchronous request processing via `@Async` annotated services, or when transactional rollbacks occur, the context is either lost or bleeds into subsequent unrelated requests on Tomcat thread pools.

You are debugging a production issue where a high-volume trading system suddenly freezes. Thread dumps reveal multiple threads are blocked inside a custom cache implementation that wraps a `ConcurrentHashMap`. The service uses Spring `@Cacheable` combined with a custom loader. The simplified structure looks like this:

java
public class CustomNestedCache {
    private final Map<String, String> cache = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

    public String getValue(String key) {
        return cache.computeIfAbsent(key, k -> {
            if (k.startsWith("derived-")) {
                return "derived-val";
            }
            // Recursive lookup for fallback dependencies
            return getValue("derived-" + k);
        });
    }
}
